{{Refimprove|date=April 2017}}
A '''Cobra probe''' is a device to measure the [[pressure]] and [[velocity]] components of a moving [[fluid]]. It is a multi-holed pressure probe with rotational axis of the probe shaft coplanar with the measurement plane of the instrument.  Because of this geometry, when the instrument is rotated around the shaft's axis, the measurement elements of the probe remain in the same location.  The name cobra probe comes from the shape of the probe head which gives it this property.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Chen|first1=J|title=Cobra probe measurements of mean velocities, Reynolds stresses and higher-order velocity correlations in pipe flow|journal=Experimental Thermal and Fluid Science|date=May 2000|volume=21|issue=4|pages=206–217|url=https://dx.doi.org/10.1016/S0894-1777(00)00004-2|accessdate=5 April 2017}}</ref>

Cobra probes come in three-, four-, and five-hole configurations, the former used for two-dimensional flow measurement, the latter two for three-dimensional flow measurement.  In the three-hole kind of instrument, there are two [[Yaw angle|yaw]] direction tubes which are chamfered and [[silver]] soldered symmetrically on the two sides of a pitot tube. It is otherwise similar to the other kinds of [[yawmeter]]s.  In the four- and five-hole configurations, the central pitot tube is surrounded by three or four chamfered tubes, respectively.

